Combat

Combat Core
•	Deterministic outcomes.
•	Each combatant has two stats:
o	Thoughness → How much Strength must be accumulated before Health is lost.


Weak: Chaplain, Scholar and Doctor
Though: Marine, Brute and Sapper
Normal: All others
o	Health → 100 (full) to 0 (death)
•	Resolution sequence:.
	
Combat resolves in rounds.
•	Vigilance / Surprise → vigilance prevents surprise but costs TP; targeted vigilance = stronger vs. one target, weaker vs. others.
•	Sanity → depressed = weaker Strength; cultists may fake weakness.

2.	Each round, both sides simultaneously apply their Strength. Strength is based on the weapon of each combatant and is affected by various public and secret modifiers. The base attack of an unarmed attack is the combatant’s Thoughness.

3.	Strength reduces the opponent’s Thoughness.

4.	If a combatant’s Thoughness drops to 0 →
    	They lose Health.
    	Their Thoughness is restored to full for the next round.
    
5.	Combat continues until one side’s Health reaches 0. ( OR PUSH HARD STANCE )
•	Persistence:

o	Thoughness depletion carries between rounds of the same combat.

o	At the end of combat (fight concluded), all surviving combatants’ Thoughness is reset to full.

o	Only Health damage persists outside combat.
________________________________________
Combat Options
•	Attack types:
o	Kill → higher Strength, lethal at 0 Health.
o	Stun → weaker Strength, incapacitates at 0 Health.

•	Defensive counters:
o	Default vs. stun = stun counter.
o	Override = kill counter (adds Strength, but risks killing a non-lethal attacker).
•	Stances:
o	Hit-and-run → disengages immediately if Strength gap is too low; attacker avoids damage and likely avoids identification.
o	Push hard → attacker continues until losing is inevitable, then flees; if no kill achieved, they are identified.
o	To the end → small Strength boost; attacker refuses to flee — if they lose, they die (or are stunned if defending against stun).
________________________________________
Hidden Modifiers

•	Role base Thoughness → Fighters are harder to wear down; support roles weaker.
________________________________________
Information After Combat
•	If defender dies → no info is public; attacker controls narrative. Dead player is only told “you died.”
•	If defender survives, alone with attacker → only Health state of both is public; either can claim self-defense.
•	If witnesses → they get hard proof of who attacked first, but this proof is private; they may lie when reporting.




		
 
Information after an attack
If the defender dies
•	The dead player receives no information about how or why they died — just the fact of death.
•	This prevents out-of-game “death reports” from leaking combat details.
•	Dead players can still participate in post-death chat (ghost mode), staying engaged without revealing any privileged info.
If the defender survives and was alone with attacker
•	Only public fact: both players’ post-combat physical states.
•	No mechanical way to prove who attacked first; either can claim self-defense.
If there are witnesses
•	Witnesses receive hard proof of who initiated the attack — visible only to them.
•	This proof is not shared mechanically with the rest of the crew; the witness can tell the truth or lie.
•	Both loyal and cultist witnesses can choose to lie —
o	Cultists: to protect a fellow cultist or frame a loyal.
o	Loyal: to shield a loyal attacker they believe acted justifiably against a suspected cultist.


